Procerain (Pc) (

) and Procerain B (PcB) (Singh et al., 2010) are two major proteases of 

Calotropis procera

(Asclepiadeae tribe of Apocyanaceae family) latex, a widespread tropical plant. Plant parts including the latex has been shown to be useful in treatment of different ailments (

; 

). Both these enzymes have been characterized extensively for their biochemical properties (

; Singh et al., 2010), substrate specificity (

; Singh et al., 2010), stability (

, 

; 

) and industrial applications (

; 

; 

; Abhay Narayan 

). However, the enzymes are reported to be vulnerable to autolytic degradation (

; 

; Singh et al., 2010) and hence the purification of the enzymes was reported at 4 
◦
C in the presence of reversible inhibitor like sodium tetrathionate in order to prevent autodigestion during purification process. The autocatalytic inactivation of Pc and PcB have been reported by (

) and (Singh et al., 2010), respectively, in presence of reducing agent, 50 mM β- ME. For Pc, it occurs at lower concentration of the protein (
<
0.55 mg
/mL) after prolonged incubation of 48 h at pH 8.0 and 37 
◦
C, while for PcB, it was relatively rapid. PcB loses 50% of activity in 5 h at concentration of
>
0.2 mg
/mL in presence of 50 mM β- ME at 37 
◦
C (

; Singh et al., 2010). The same studies, on the other hand, showed high thermal and pH stabilities for these two enzymes. Hence, the mechanism for their autoproteolysis remains elusive and possibly occur in one of the conditions reported earlier for other proteases (

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

). For instance, it could be because of activation of the enzyme or its global denaturation or presence of susceptible cleavage site in structurally unperturbed molecule. In view of all these different possible ways for autolytic degradation of these proteases, it was felt necessary to study the kinetic stability of Pc and PcB in detail with respect to their autoproteolytic degradation. Moreover, since 

Calotropis

cysteine proteases are of great importance due to their potential applications in different industries like food (

; 

; 

), pharmaceutical (

; 

), leather (Lop´ez et al., 2017; 

) or detergents (

), stability towards auto-degradation becomes all the more important aspect for their practical use.

The enzymes were incubated for 3 min with individual or mixture of the components of SDS-PAGE sample buffer in boiling condition in presence or absence of E-64. After the incubation, E-64 was added to all the samples devoid of E-64. All these samples were later subjected to SDS-PAGE after treating them with sample buffer. The results of the same are presented in Fig. 1A and B . The results showed that in the absence of E-64, a potent inhibitor of cysteine proteases, complete disappearance of Pc protein band was observed on gel upon boiling in the individual components of SDS-PAGE sample preparation buffer viz. 50 mM Tris-Cl pH 6.8, 2% SDS, 150 mM β- ME or their mixture i.e., 2% SDS and 150 mM β- ME. For PcB, partial disappearance of the protein band was observed on the gel when samples were boiled in 50 mM Tris pH 6.8 and 2% SDS and were completely disappeared in 150 mM β- ME and combination of 2% SDS and 150 mM β- ME. On the contrary, addition of E-64 during sample preparation led to appearance of protein bands on the gel for both the enzymes. The possible reason for the observed phenomenon could be autodigestion of the enzymes during sample preparation. Autoproteolysis of papain-like proteases have been reported upon their activation in the presence of reducing agent like β- ME (
;
). However, the SDS-PAGE profile shows that Pc undergoes autolysis within 3 min in boiling conditions and the autolysis is irrespective of presence of β- ME. On the other hand, PcB exhibits complete autodigestion only in the presence of β- ME. This differential response of the two enzymes to the aforementioned conditions leading to autolysis makes it interesting to understand the basic mechanism behind autodigestion and to find out, if it is linked to kinetic stability of the proteins.

Thermal denaturation of the enzymes was studied in real-time using differential scanning fluorimetry (DSF). It was carried out for enzymes alone or in combination with GdnHCl and/or β- ME, in presence and absence of E-64 (
Fig. 3A–D
and Supplementary 
Fig. 3A and B
). The denaturation curves of native proteins showed that thermal denaturation of Pc starts at 80 
◦
C, while that of PcB, above 75 
◦
C (
Fig. 3A and B
). The transition temperature of Pc and PcB was not affected due to the presence of E-64. In presence of β- ME, the transition occurred at lower temperatures, with the effect more distinguishable in case of Pc than that in PcB (
Fig. 3A and B
). The increase in fluorescence was higher in case of E-64 inhibited proteins than that of the uninhibited proteins. The relative increase in fluorescence intensity of Pc upon unfolding in presence of β- ME was higher than that observed for native protein, suggesting increased degree of unfolding. Surprisingly, the reverse was observed for PcB, wherein the relative fluorescence intensity decreased in presence of β- ME compared to native protein. Since the thermal denaturation could not be studied in presence of SDS (due to interaction of the dye, SYPRO Orange, with SDS), we used another denaturant GdnHCl to study the same. In case of Pc, for unknown reasons, we could not observe any significant increase in fluorescence irrespective of concentrations of GdnHCl and presence of β- ME and/or E- 
64 in
the mix subjected to DSF studies (Supplementary 
Fig. 3A and B
). Although just a small spur of increase in fluorescence was observed during enzyme alone subjected to denaturation in presence of GdnHCl (Supplementary 
Fig. 1B
), it is not significant to suggest the denaturation temperature in those conditions (Supplementary 
Fig. 1B
). Nevertheless, for PcB, increase in concentration of GdnHCl resulted in decrease in melting temperature and presence of β- ME did not influence thermal denaturation profile of the proteins (
Fig. 3C and D
).

Bromelain and PcB were found to be sensitive to autolysis than Pc and papain in presence of reducing agent, β- ME (
Fig. 6A–F
). Reduction of disulphide bonds in PcB or bromelain has possibly made the proteins very sensitive to proteolytic digestion. In order to understand this phenomenon, we examined the solvent accessible surface area (SASA) of each of the three conserved disulphide bonds in the crystal structures of papain and bromelain and the predicted structures of Pc and PcB (Supplementary Table 1). Higher accessibility of β- ME to sulphur atoms of disulphide bonds may facilitate the reduction of the bonds. We expected that SASA would be significantly higher for the disulphide bonds in the structures of the enzymes which are sensitive to autolysis in presence of β- ME. We, however, found no correlation of sensitivity of the proteins to autoproteolysis with their respective solvent accessibility parameters (Supplementary Table 1). This may be due to dynamic nature of the proteins. SASA may show the correlation with autolysis sensitivity in presence of β- ME when we consider the dynamic nature of the proteins.

We further examined the dynamicity using molecular simulations of PcB which is more sensitive to autolysis in presence of reducing agent than Pc. We performed 500 ns molecular dynamics simulations on PcB in presence and absence of disulphide bonds. Molecular dynamics results indicate that both simulations for PcB have converged (Supplementary 
Fig. 4
) and root mean square distance (RMSD) remains fairly stable for the last 100 ns? We found that the PcB lacking disulphide bonds has a higher RMSD value as compared to PcB with disulphide bonds (Supplementary 
Fig. 6
). Radius of gyration for both the proteins shows that none of the two proteins is losing its integrity during the simulations (Supplementary 
Fig.5
). Further, effects of reduced cysteine residues are directly visible by root mean square fluctuation (RMSF) of Cα of the structures during 500 ns simulations in both the forms (Supplementary 
Fig. 6
). The loop regions (residues 147–153, residues 185–195 and residues 216–225) in PcB structure lacking disulphide bonds show significantly higher fluctuation of protein backbone as compared to PcB containing disulphide bonds (Supplementary Fig. 7). This backbone fluctuation is attributed to reduction of cysteine residues of disulphide bond I and II.

Autocatalysis has been reported for many proteases (

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

; 

) including cysteine proteases. For few enzymes, autocatalysis can be a mechanism for its activation, like catheptic enzymes (

). In other enzymes, it is a process leading to irreversible inactivation of the enzyme which is disadvantageous for industrial applications of many enzymes 
viz.
thermolysin or trypsin (

; 

). Thus, the phenomenon is of great interest to study the vulnerable cleavage sites in such industrially important enzymes and countering it by protein engineering approach. Although there is no generalized mechanism for autodegradation of proteases, partial unfolding of the enzymes has been reported to be the pre-requisite for their autolysis (

; 

). In few cases, however, autodegradation has been reported to occur in conditions optimum for protease activity in which the global protein structure is unperturbed, as in the case of thermolysin (

), TNA1_POP (

) and kallikrein (

), which are known to undergo autolysis at their optimum temperatures. In another example, autoproteolytic inactivation of HtrA protease of 
E. coli
has been suggested to occur by the hyperactivation of the enzyme through allosteric activation by the proteolytic products of its substrates (

). In view of so many different ways the enzymes are reported to undergo autolytic degradation, we studied this phenomenon in two proteases, Pc and PcB, from 

Calotropis procera

.

It is worth mentioning here that both the proteins are very stable to thermal denaturation in non-reducing conditions. However, presence of β- ME in the concentration range of 50–100 mM could destabilize the enzymes in 2–3 h and bring about autolytic degradation at 50 ◦ C. Pc and PcB both share high sequence identities with other plant cysteine proteases of C1 family, like papain, bromelain, actinidin and ficin. Homology modelling of Pc and PcB shows that they share similar structures to other plant cysteine proteases. It is important to point out that papain does not get inactivated in presence of β- ME (320 mM) unless it is partially unfolded by 8 M urea (
) at 37 ◦ C. In bromelain, however, inactivation is reported at 50 ◦ C in presence of 2 mM DTT leading to loss of 80% activity in 1.5 h (
). In view of this, we also compared the kinetic stability of Pc, PcB, papain and bromelain in the presence of different concentrations of β- ME at 50 ◦ C up to 2 h ( Fig. 6A–F ). We found bromelain was the most susceptible to inactivation in presence of β- ME (100 mM), followed by PcB. This is in agreement with the observations of (
) for bromelain. Pc showed marginal inactivation at 200 mM β- ME after 2 h. Papain was found to be the most resistant towards inactivation even in the presence of 400 mM of β- ME after 2 h. The autoproteolysis was also distinctly observed only for bromelain and PcB as seen from their SDS-PAGE profiles ( Fig. 6A–F ). Crystal structures of papain-like proteases such as papain, bromelain and actinidin (PDB ids: 1PPN, 6YCG, 3P5W, respectively) show the presence of three conserved disulphide bonds and these are primarily responsible for providing structural stability to the proteins from thermal denaturation (Supplementary Fig. 2 and Supplementary Table 1). Homology models of Pc and PcB also show presence of three conserved disulphide bonds in them. Higher concentration of β- ME reduce the disulphide bonds in the structure of a protein and make the connecting loops or other adjoining structural elements more flexible, which is enhanced by higher temperature. This could act as a nucleating point for the thermal denaturation of the protein and make the polypeptide regions more accessible to the protease. The first cleavage in the polypeptide could start the cascading events of further denaturation and proteolytic cleavages. Interestingly, in spite of presence of exactly three numbers of disulphide bonds in papain, Pc, PcB and bromelain, the latter two proteins are distinctly susceptible to proteolysis. Therefore, we thought that the solvent accessibility to the disulphide bonds in the structures could be the governing parameters for the access of β- ME to the bonds. Hence, we checked the surface solvent accessibility of the disulphide bonds in the crystal structures of papain and bromelain and homology models of Pc and PcB. We found no correlation of the solvent accessibility and the reducing agent susceptibility of the proteins. Thus, mere solvent accessibility and that too in the static 3-D structures may not be sufficient parameter to provide clue for their differential susceptibility to proteolysis in presence of reducing agent. We later performed 500 ns molecular simulations on PcB protein which is more susceptible to the proteolysis than Pc. We found that RMSF values, a good indicator of backbone flexibility, is more for the loops around the position of disulphide bonds in disulphide-free model than disulphide-containing model (Supplementary Fig. 6 and Supplementary Fig. 7). This flexibility could provide the accessibility to the proteolysis and hence PcB in presence of higher concentration of β- ME lacking disulphide bonds are prone to thermal denaturation and proteolysis. Overall, the start of the conformational flexibility either governed by denaturant like SDS and GdnHCl or reducing agent like β- ME may bring about the start point of proteolysis and further cycle of denaturation and proteolysis. However, our findings regarding differential sensitivity towards autoproteolysis of papain-like proteases i.e. C1 family proteases in the presence of β- ME can be helpful for deciding the conditions for their industrial applications.

Azocasein, Sypro-Orange, sodium dodecyl sulphate (SDS), guanidine hydrochloirde (GdnHCl), β- mercaptoethanol (β- ME) were obtained from Sigma (
USA
). CM-Sepharose, Superdex 200 were obtained from Cytiva (
USA
). All other chemicals used were of Analytical Grade.

Homogeneity of the individual protein and molecular weight of the polypeptide was analysed by SDS-PAGE (

) using 15% (w/v) acrylamide resolving gel and standard proteins as molecular weight markers (Merck Genie, 
India
). Protein denaturation was carried out in the presence of 10–100 μM of E 64 wherever necessary either in sample buffer or individual component of sample buffer.

Pc and PcB share 88.5% sequence identity between them and both of them share about 47% sequence identity with papain (Supplementary 
Fig.2
). Pc and PcB structural models were prepared by homology modelling using SWISS-MODEL server (

) using default parameters and template as papain structure (PDB id:1PPN) (Supplementary 
Fig. 3
). The molecular dynamics (MD) systems for PcB with and without disulphide bonds were generated using GROMACS 5.1 (

) using CHARMM27 all-atom force field (

). The solvated systems were prepared in cubic boxes with one side of 10 Å which was filled with ~13,000 spc 216 water models (

) for each system. Depending upon the overall charge on the protein, an appropriate number of Na 
+
or Cl ions were added to neutralize the system. Additionally, 0.1 M concentration of NaCl was achieved by replacing water molecules. This was followed by energy minimization using the steepest descent algorithm with 1000 kJ/mol/nm tolerance. The temperature and pressure equilibration runs were performed using Berendsen thermostat (

) and Parrinello-Rahman (

) pressure coupling algorithms, respectively. Both the runs were performed using LINCS holonomic constraints on the protein for 10 ns with step size of 2 fs, while using 
1 nm
cut-off distances for both short range electrostatics and van der Waals cut-off during neighbour searching via the PME electrostatics treatment while temperature and pressure equilibration and MD run were per formed using the leap-frog integrator (

). Final MD run for both PcB with and without disulphide bonds systems was performed for 500 ns (Supplementary 
Fig. 4
and 
5
).
